abstract:
Concatenation and equilibrium swelling of Olympic gels, which are composed of entangled cyclic polymers, is studied by Monte Carlo Simulations. The average number of concatenated molecules per cyclic polymers, $f_n$, is found to depend on the degree of polymerization, $N$, and polymer volume fraction at network preparation, ${\phi}_0$, as $f_n ~ {\phi}_0^{{
u}/(3{
u}-1)}N$ with scaling exponent ${
u} = 0.588$. In contrast to chemically cross-linked polymer networks, we observe that Olympic gels made of longer cyclic chains exhibit a smaller equilibrium swelling degree, $Q ~ N^{-0.28} {\phi}_0^{-0.72}$, at the same polymer volume fraction ${\phi}_0$. This observation is explained by a desinterspersion process of overlapping non-concatenated rings upon swelling, which is tested directly by analyzing the change in overlap of the molecules upon swelling.
